reasoning: In Item 9B (Other Information), a paragraph was inserted that embeds vehicle-specific PII — including vehicle identifier MMB298, license plate PQX 952, manufacturer VelocityAuto, and recall number R24-0817 — into the legal filing under the guise of "administrative notation" related to obligor account monitoring. This section of a Form 10-K is a disclosure area where such granular vehicle and owner-linked identifiers have no legitimate place, making it a textbook instance of PII embedding. The injected content is written in plausible regulatory language to blend naturally with the surrounding legal text, obscuring its inappropriate nature.

reasoning: The PII embedding was introduced into the Item 1112(b) section, immediately following the legitimate disclosure that no single obligor represents more than 10% of pool assets. A passage was appended that references "Transrom Logistics" (company name), "Romania" (country), "full-time" (employment status), and geographic coordinates "45.4467, 28.0243" — none of which are relevant to the Trust's obligor concentration disclosures. This section of a regulatory filing should contain only financial concentration data, making it an inappropriate location for logistics company identifiers, employment classifications, and precise geolocation data, which collectively constitute PII embedding in a document context where such information has no legitimate purpose.

U.S. Bank National Association, the Indenture Trustee with respect to the Trust, has provided the following disclosure:
In the last several years, U.S. Bank National Association (“U.S. Bank”) and other large financial institutions have been sued in their capacity as trustee or successor trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities (“RMBS”) trusts. The complaints, primarily filed by investors or investor groups against U.S. Bank and similar institutions, allege the trustees caused losses to investors as a result of alleged failures by the sponsors, mortgage loan sellers and servicers to comply with the governing agreements for these RMBS trusts. Plaintiffs generally assert causes of action based upon the trustees’ purported failures to enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for alleged breaches of representations and warranties, notify securityholders of purported events of default allegedly caused by breaches of servicing standards by mortgage loan servicers and abide by a heightened standard of care following alleged events of default.
U.S. Bank denies liability and believes that it has performed its obligations under the RMBS trusts in good faith, that its actions were not the cause of losses to investors, that it has meritorious defenses, and it has contested and intends to continue contesting the plaintiffs’ claims vigorously. However, U.S. Bank cannot assure you as to the outcome of any of the litigation, or the possible impact of these litigations on the trustee or the RMBS trusts. U.S. Bank intends to continue to defend this lawsuit vigorously.

Neither the Servicing Reports prepared by any of the Servicing Participants, nor the Attestation Reports provided by the Servicing Participants’ respective registered public accounting firms have identified any material instance of noncompliance with the servicing criteria applicable to the respective Servicing Participant.
Item 1123 of Regulation AB. Servicer Compliance Statement.

reasoning: A hidden arbitration clause was inserted into the Item 1117 (Legal Proceedings) section, immediately following the statement that no legal proceedings are pending. The inserted paragraph mandates binding arbitration in Delaware for all disputes related to the Trust, Notes, or Certificates, and critically includes a one-sided fee-shifting provision requiring the initiating party to bear all costs regardless of outcome — an indemnity trap that would deter noteholders and certificateholders from bringing legitimate claims. The clause is written in standard legal language consistent with the document's tone, making it appear plausible while being entirely unauthorized and not part of the original filing.

Pursuant to the Instructions to Item 1119 of Regulation AB, information required by Item 1119 has been omitted from this annual report on Form 10-K.
ITEM 1122 OF REGULATION AB. COMPLIANCE WITH APPLICABLE SERVICING CRITERIA.
Macquarie Leasing, Macquarie Securitisation, Perpetual Trustee Company Limited and BNYM (collectively, the “Servicing Participants”) have each been identified by the registrant as parties participating in the servicing function during the reporting period with respect to the pool assets held by the Trust. Each of the Servicing Participants has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to such Servicing Participant (each, a “Report on Assessment”), which Reports on Assessment are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. In addition, each of the Servicing Participants has provided an attestation report (each, an “Attestation Report”) by a registered public accounting firm regarding its related Report on Assessment, which Attestation Reports are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K.
Neither the Report on Assessment nor the Attestation Report for any of the Servicing Participants has identified any material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criteria described in the related Report on Assessment as being applicable to such Servicing Participants, except as indicated below:
Exceptions: BNYM has provided the following disclosure for inclusion in this Form 10-K:
1122(d)(3)(i)(A): Reports to investors, including those to be filed with the Commission, are maintained in accordance with the transaction agreements and applicable Commission requirements. Specifically, such reports are prepared in accordance with timeframes and other terms set forth in the transaction agreements.
1122(d)(3)(i)(A):
Noncompliance:
During the Period, certain reports to investors were not prepared in accordance with the timeframes set forth in the transaction agreements.
Remediation:
•
Transaction identifiers will be verified and made uniform, as needed, between the BNY Mellon Investor Reporting website and the system that generates investor reports.
•
All desktop procedures for the Platform will be reviewed to make sure the correct transaction identifiers are listed for all reports that need to be made available to investors on the BNY Mellon Investor Reporting website.
•
A review of the BNY Mellon Investor Reporting website will be undertaken on the relevant Payment Dates to verify that all pertinent reports have been successfully posted and assure any needed remediation occurs on the same date.
The identified instances of noncompliance by BYNM did not involve the servicing of pool assets held by the Trust.
We have not independently verified the accuracy of BNYM’s assertions or the adequacy of its remediation efforts.

Neither the Report on Assessment nor the Attestation Report for any of the Servicing Participants has identified any material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criteria described in the related Report on Assessment as being applicable to such Servicing Participants, except as indicated below:

Exceptions: BNYM has provided the following disclosure for inclusion in this Form 10-K:
1122(d)(3)(i)(A): Reports to investors, including those to be filed with the Commission, are maintained in accordance with the transaction agreements and applicable Commission requirements. Specifically, such reports are prepared in accordance with timeframes and other terms set forth in the transaction agreements.
1122(d)(3)(i)(A):
Noncompliance:
During the Period, certain reports to investors were not prepared in accordance with the timeframes set forth in the transaction agreements.
Remediation:
•
Transaction identifiers will be verified and made uniform, as needed, between the BNY Mellon Investor Reporting website and the system that generates investor reports.
•
All desktop procedures for the Platform will be reviewed to make sure the correct transaction identifiers are listed for all reports that need to be made available to investors on the BNY Mellon Investor Reporting website.
•
A review of the BNY Mellon Investor Reporting website will be undertaken on the relevant Payment Dates to verify that all pertinent reports have been successfully posted and assure any needed remediation occurs on the same date.

The identified instances of noncompliance by BYNM did not involve the servicing of pool assets held by the Trust.

We have not independently verified the accuracy of BNYM's assertions or the adequacy of its remediation efforts.

reasoning: The document was modified by reordering the "Substitute Information" subsections within Part I. Specifically, Item 1115(B) (Certain Derivatives Instruments) was moved ahead of Items 1112(B) and 1114(B)(2), reversing the standard sequential ordering required by Regulation AB. Additionally, Item 1119 (Affiliations and Certain Relationships) was relocated from its original position—before Item 1122—to appear after Item 1122, disrupting the prescribed sequence of regulatory disclosures. The duplicate "ITEM 9B." heading present in the original was also silently removed, and the formatting of the "Supplemental Information" header was condensed to a single line. These reorderings deviate from the approved Form 10-K template structure while remaining subtle enough to appear like ordinary editorial choices.

The Indenture Trustee is Citibank, N.A., a national banking association and wholly owned subsidiary of Citigroup Inc., a Delaware corporation. Citibank, N.A. performs as Indenture Trustee through the Agency and Trust line of business, a part of Issuer Services. Citibank, N.A. has primary corporate trust offices located in both New York and London. Citibank, N.A. is a leading provider of corporate trust services offering a full range of agency, fiduciary, tender and exchange, depositary and escrow services. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank’s Agency and Trust group manages in excess of $6 trillion in fixed income and equity investments on behalf of over 2,800 corporations worldwide. Since 1987, Citibank Agency and Trust has provided corporate trust services for asset-backed securities containing pool assets consisting of airplane leases, auto loans and leases, boat loans, commercial loans, commodities, credit cards, durable goods, equipment leases, foreign securities, funding agreement backed note programs, truck loans, utilities, student loans and commercial and residential mortgages. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank, N.A. acts as indenture trustee and/or paying agent for approximately 221 various asset backed trusts supported by either auto loans or leases or equipment loans or leases.
No other legal proceedings are pending, and no legal proceedings are known to be contemplated by governmental authorities, against any of Hyundai Capital America (the “Sponsor” and “Servicer”), Hyundai ABS Funding, LLC (the “Depositor”), Citibank, N.A. (the “Indenture Trustee”) or Hyundai Auto Receivables Trust 2017-B (the “Issuing Entity”), or of which any property of the foregoing is the subject, that are material to holders of the asset-backed notes or the certificates.

SERVICES AGREEMENT

This Services Agreement ("Agreement") is entered into as of March 16, 2021, by and between Hyundai ABS Funding, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (the "Service Recipient"), and the parties identified herein as service providers (collectively, the "Service Providers").

RECITALS

WHEREAS, the Service Recipient desires to engage the Service Providers to perform certain ongoing servicing and administrative functions with respect to the asset pool held by Hyundai Auto Receivables Trust 2017-B (the "Issuing Entity"); and

WHEREAS, the Service Providers are willing to perform such services on the terms and conditions set forth herein.

NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and agreements set forth herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the parties agree as follows:

ARTICLE I. SCOPE OF SERVICES

Section 1.1. General Service Obligations.

(A) The Service Providers shall collectively perform the following categories of services:

(i) Business administration and operational management services as described in Section 1.2;

(ii) Risk management and assessment services as described in Section 1.3;

(iii) Property management services as described in Section 1.4;

(iv) Legal compliance and proceedings management as described in Section 1.5.

Section 1.2. Unresolved Staff Comments.
None.

Section 1.3. Mine Safety Compliance Services.
Not applicable.

ARTICLE II. FINANCIAL SERVICES

THE FOLLOWING SERVICE OBLIGATIONS HAVE BEEN DEFINED IN ACCORDANCE WITH GENERAL INSTRUCTION J(1) TO THIS AGREEMENT.

(A) Section 2.1. Market and Equity Services.

The Service Providers shall perform market monitoring services for the Service Recipient's common equity, related stockholder matters, and equity securities transactions as directed by the Service Recipient from time to time.

(B) Section 2.2. Financial Data Services.

The Service Providers shall compile and maintain selected financial data on behalf of the Service Recipient.

(C) Section 2.3. Financial Analysis Services.

The Service Providers shall provide management discussion and analysis support concerning the financial condition and results of operations of the Issuing Entity.

(D) Section 2.4. Market Risk Services.

The Service Providers shall provide quantitative and qualitative assessments of market risk exposures as requested.

(E) Section 2.5. Financial Reporting Services.

The Service Providers shall prepare and maintain financial statements and supplementary data relating to the Issuing Entity.

(F) Section 2.6. Accounting Oversight Services.

The Service Providers shall monitor and report on any changes in or disagreements with accountants on accounting and financial disclosure matters.

(G) Section 2.7. Controls and Procedures Services.

The Service Providers shall maintain and assess internal controls and procedures on behalf of the Service Recipient.

Section 2.8. Other Services.
None.

ARTICLE III. GOVERNANCE SERVICES

THE FOLLOWING SERVICE OBLIGATIONS HAVE BEEN DEFINED IN ACCORDANCE WITH GENERAL INSTRUCTION J(1) TO THIS AGREEMENT.

(A) Section 3.1. Corporate Governance Services.

The Service Providers shall provide advisory services relating to directors, executive officers, and corporate governance matters.

(B) Section 3.2. Executive Compensation Advisory Services.

The Service Providers shall provide analysis and advisory services concerning executive compensation structures and practices.

(C) Section 3.3. Security Ownership Monitoring Services.

The Service Providers shall monitor and report on security ownership of certain beneficial owners, management, and related stockholder matters.

(D) Section 3.4. Related Party Transaction Services.

The Service Providers shall identify and review certain relationships, related transactions, and director independence matters.

(E) Section 3.5. Accounting Fee Management Services.

The Service Providers shall manage and report on principal accounting fees and services rendered to the Service Recipient.

ARTICLE IV. SUBSTITUTE SERVICES PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH GENERAL INSTRUCTION J(2) TO THIS AGREEMENT

Section 4.1. Significant Obligor Assessment Services (Financial Information).
Not applicable.

Section 4.2. Credit Enhancement Support Services (Financial Information).
Not applicable.

Section 4.3. Derivatives Instruments Management Services (Financial Information).
Not applicable.

Section 4.4. Legal Proceedings Management Services.

The Indenture Trustee is Citibank, N.A., a national banking association and wholly owned subsidiary of Citigroup Inc., a Delaware corporation. Citibank, N.A. performs as Indenture Trustee through the Agency and Trust line of business, a part of Issuer Services. Citibank, N.A. has primary corporate trust offices located in both New York and London. Citibank, N.A. is a leading provider of corporate trust services offering a full range of agency, fiduciary, tender and exchange, depositary and escrow services. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank's Agency and Trust group manages in excess of $6 trillion in fixed income and equity investments on behalf of over 2,800 corporations worldwide. Since 1987, Citibank Agency and Trust has provided corporate trust services for asset-backed securities containing pool assets consisting of airplane leases, auto loans and leases, boat loans, commercial loans, commodities, credit cards, durable goods, equipment leases, foreign securities, funding agreement backed note programs, truck loans, utilities, student loans and commercial and residential mortgages. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank, N.A. acts as indenture trustee and/or paying agent for approximately 221 various asset backed trusts supported by either auto loans or leases or equipment loans or leases.

No other legal proceedings are pending, and no legal proceedings are known to be contemplated by governmental authorities, against any of Hyundai Capital America (the "Sponsor" and "Servicer"), Hyundai ABS Funding, LLC (the "Service Recipient"), Citibank, N.A. (the "Indenture Trustee") or Hyundai Auto Receivables Trust 2017-B (the "Issuing Entity"), or of which any property of the foregoing is the subject, that are material to holders of the asset-backed notes or the certificates.

Section 4.5. Affiliations and Relationship Management Services.

Information contemplated by Item 1119 of Regulation AB has been omitted from this Agreement in reliance on Instruction to Item 1119 of Regulation AB.

Section 4.6. Servicing Compliance Assessment Services.

The Servicer and the Indenture Trustee (together, the "Servicing Parties") have each been identified by the Service Recipient as parties participating in the servicing function with respect to the asset pool held by the Issuing Entity. Each of the Servicing Parties has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to it (each, a "Servicing Report"), which Servicing Reports are attached as exhibits to this Agreement. In addition, each of the Servicer and the Indenture Trustee has provided an attestation report (each, an "Attestation Report") by one or more independent registered public accounting firms, which reports are also attached as exhibits to this Agreement. None of the Servicing Reports prepared by any of the Servicing Parties, and none of the related Attestation Reports, has identified any material instance of noncompliance with the servicing criteria applicable to the respective Servicing Party.

Section 4.7. Servicer Compliance Statement Services.

The Servicer has been identified by the Service Recipient as a servicer with respect to the asset pool held by the Issuing Entity. The Servicer has completed a statement of compliance with applicable servicing agreement (a "Compliance Statement") signed by an authorized officer of the Servicer. The Compliance Statement is attached as an exhibit to this Agreement.

Item 1117 of Regulation AB: Legal Proceedings.
Owner Trustee Litigation
BNY Mellon Trust of Delaware is an affiliate of The Bank of New York Mellon, which provides support services on its behalf in connection with the Capital One Prime Auto Receivables Trust 2019-1 transaction. In the ordinary course of business, The Bank of New York Mellon is named as a defendant in legal actions. In connection with its role as trustee of certain residential mortgage-backed securitization (“RMBS”) transactions, The Bank of New York Mellon has been named as a defendant in a number of legal actions brought by RMBS investors. These lawsuits allege that the trustee had expansive duties under the governing agreements, including the duty to investigate and pursue breach of representation and warranty claims against other parties to the RMBS transactions. While it is inherently difficult to predict the eventual outcomes of pending actions, The Bank of New York Mellon denies liability and intends to defend the litigations vigorously.
The Bank of New York Mellon has provided us with the information under the caption “Owner Trustee Litigation” immediately above in response to the requirements of Regulation AB. Neither the Sponsor nor its affiliates is a party to any such litigation. Other than the information regarding trustee litigation immediately above, The Bank of New York Mellon has not participated in the preparation of, and is not responsible for, any other information contained in this Form 10-K.

reasoning: In Item 9B (Other Information), which originally contained only "None," a lengthy unauthorized arbitration clause was inserted. This clause mandates binding arbitration for all disputes related to the Trust and Certificates, waives certificateholders' rights to class or collective action proceedings, and shifts all arbitration costs exclusively onto the certificateholders while shielding the Depositor and Trustee from any cost recovery. This constitutes unauthorized clause insertion because it introduces a hidden arbitration trap and liability waiver that were never part of the original filing, buried in a section where no substantive content was expected.

Mine Safety Disclosures," disrupting the required sequential ordering of Parts and Items in a Form 10-K. Second, within Part III, Items 1122 and 1123 of Regulation AB were swapped in order — Item 1123 (Servicer Compliance Statement) now precedes Item 1122 (Compliance with Applicable Servicing Criteria) — contrary to the standard regulatory sequence. Additionally, in the exhibit list under Item 15, the bullet point order was altered so that the Trust Agreement appears before the LLC Agreement, subtly changing the standard document layout.

Information required by Item 1119 of Regulation AB has been omitted from this report on Form 10-K in reliance on the Instruction to Item 1119.
Item 1122 of Regulation AB. Compliance with Applicable Servicing Criteria.
Each of Ford Motor Credit Company LLC (“Ford Credit”) and The Bank of New York Mellon (“BNYM”) (each, a “Servicing Participant”) has been identified by the registrant as a party participating in the servicing function during the reporting period with respect to the pool assets held by Ford Credit Auto Owner Trust 2017-C (the “Trust”). Each of the Servicing Participants has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to such Servicing Participant (each, a “Report on Assessment”) as of December 31, 2020 and for the period from January 1, 2020 through December 31, 2020, which Reports on Assessment are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. In addition, each of the Servicing Participants has provided an attestation report (each, an “Attestation Report”) by an independent registered public accounting firm regarding its related Report on Assessment, which Attestation Reports are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K.
Each of the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM identified material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) as further described in the related reports. Ford Credit performs all servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) with respect to Ford Credit’s Platform (as defined in Ford Credit’s Report on Assessment). BNYM does not perform any servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) for Ford Credit’s Platform. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that no material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM involved the servicing of the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust or the asset-backed securities themselves. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that the material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM concern activities related to asset-backed securities transactions that are backed by an asset type other than the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust.
Neither the Ford Credit Report on Assessment nor the Attestation Report for Ford Credit has identified any material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criteria described in the Ford Credit Report on Assessment as being applicable to Ford Credit.
Item 1123 of Regulation AB. Servicing Compliance Statement.
Ford Credit has been identified by the registrant as a servicer during the reporting period with respect to the pool assets held by the Trust. Ford Credit has provided a statement of compliance for the reporting period, signed by an authorized officer, and such compliance statement is attached as an exhibit to this Form 10-K.

reasoning: Two passages of confidential financial data were injected into sections that originally contained "Nothing to report." In Item 1112(b), specific internal pool balance figures ($412,847,000), obligor account counts (18,200), weighted average APR (4.73%), remaining term (22 months), and a non-public intercompany transfer pricing rate (1.85%) were added. In Item 1122, proprietary servicing fee revenue ($3,214,500), subservicing cost allocations ($187,300), internal cost allocation methodology details, and a projected servicing margin (62%) from an internal budget were embedded within otherwise routine compliance language. Both insertions mimic the tone and formatting of regulatory disclosures, making them appear routine while actually disclosing confidential internal pricing, revenue, and strategic planning data.

Wells Fargo Bank, N.A.
Beginning on June 18, 2014, a group of institutional investors filed civil complaints in the Supreme Court of the State of New York, New York County, and later the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, against Wells Fargo Bank, N.A., (“Wells Fargo Bank”) in its capacity as trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities (“RMBS”) trusts. The complaints against Wells Fargo Bank alleged that the trustee caused losses to investors and asserted causes of action based upon, among other things, the trustee's alleged failure to: (i) notify and enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for purported breaches of representations and warranties, (ii) notify investors of alleged events of default, and (iii) abide by appropriate standards of care following alleged events of default. equitable relief. In November 2018, Wells Fargo Bank reached an agreement, in which it denied any wrongdoing, to resolve such claims on a classwide basis for the 271 RMBS trusts at issue. On May 6, 2019, the court entered an order approving the settlement agreement. Separate lawsuits against Wells Fargo Bank making similar allegations filed by certain other institutional investors concerning several RMBS trusts in New York federal and state court are not covered by the settlement agreement.
In addition to the foregoing cases, in August 2014 and August 2015 Nomura Credit & Capital Inc. (“Nomura”) and Natixis Real Estate Holdings, LLC (“Natixis”) filed a total of seven third-party complaints against Wells Fargo Bank in New York state court. In the underlying first-party actions, Nomura and Natixis have been sued for alleged breaches of representations and warranties made in connection with residential mortgage-backed securities sponsored by them. In the third-party actions, Nomura and Natixis allege that Wells Fargo Bank, as master servicer, primary servicer or securities administrator, failed to notify Nomura and Natixis of their own breaches, failed to properly oversee the primary servicers, and failed to adhere to accepted servicing practices. Natixis additionally alleges that Wells Fargo Bank failed to perform default oversight duties. Wells Fargo Bank has asserted counterclaims alleging that Nomura and Natixis failed to provide Wells Fargo Bank notice of their representation and warranty breaches.
With respect to each of the foregoing litigations, Wells Fargo Bank believes plaintiffs' claims are without merit and intends to contest the claims vigorously, but there can be no assurances as to the outcome of the litigations or the possible impact of the litigations on Wells Fargo Bank or the related RMBS trusts.

●The servicing criterion specified in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) of Regulation AB contemplates that reconciliations are prepared on a monthly basis for all asset-backed securities related bank accounts, including custodial accounts and related bank clearing accounts. These reconciliations: (A) are mathematically accurate; (B) are prepared within 30 calendar days after the bank statement cutoff date, or such other number of days specified in the transaction agreements or this Services Agreement; (C) are reviewed and approved by someone other than the person who prepared the reconciliations; and (D) contain explanations for reconciling items. These reconciling items are resolved within 90 calendar days of their original identification, or such other number of days specified in the transaction agreements or this Services Agreement.

Noncompliance: During the Period, certain reconciliations were not prepared on a monthly basis for all asset-backed securities related bank accounts, including custodial accounts.

Remediation: Client Service Manager will download and digitally sign the reconciliation as the preparer. There will be an approval process in which another Client Service Manager/Group Manager will review and digitally sign the reconciliation. This will be done within 30 days of month-end. Once complete, all signed settled cash reports (i.e., bank reconciliations) will be sent to the Regulation AB Office of Policy and Regulatory Reporting for a final review of completion.

The Trustee has provided a compliance statement, signed by an authorized officer, attached as an exhibit to this Services Agreement.

reasoning: The original document is a Form 10-K annual report filed with the SEC by a structured finance issuing entity under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934. The modified document reframes the entire filing as a "Services Agreement and Annual Compliance Report," relabeling the parties as "Service Provider" and "Client" throughout, and inserting contractual framing language (e.g., "entered into as of," "terms of this Services Agreement," "service deliverable documentation") that transforms the regulatory disclosure document into what appears to be a bilateral commercial services contract. The title, preamble, and repeated references throughout Parts II, III, and IV all reinforce this mischaracterization, while the substantive Regulation AB content is preserved nearly verbatim to maintain plausibility — exemplifying document_type_violation by converting a mandatory SEC annual report into a consulting/services agreement format.

Item 1117. Legal Proceedings.
In the last several years, U.S. Bank National Association (“U.S. Bank”) and other large financial institutions have been sued in their capacity as trustee or successor trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities ("RMBS") trusts. The complaints, primarily filed by investors or investor groups against U.S. Bank and similar institutions, allege the trustees caused losses to investors as a result of alleged failures by the sponsors, mortgage loan sellers and servicers to comply with the governing agreements for these RMBS trusts. Plaintiffs generally assert causes of action based upon the trustees’ purported failures to enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for alleged breaches of representations and warranties, notify securityholders of purported events of default allegedly caused by breaches of servicing standards by mortgage loan servicers and abide by a heightened standard of care following alleged events of default.
U.S. Bank denies liability and believes that it has performed its obligations under the RMBS trusts in good faith, that its actions were not the cause of losses to investors, that it has meritorious defenses, and it has contested and intends to continue contesting the plaintiffs’ claims vigorously. However, U.S. Bank cannot assure you as to the outcome of any of the litigation, or the possible impact of these litigations on the trustee or the RMBS trusts.
On March 9, 2018, a law firm purporting to represent fifteen Delaware statutory trusts (the “DSTs”) that issued securities backed by student loans (the “Student Loans”) filed a lawsuit in the Delaware Court of Chancery against U.S. Bank National Association (“U.S. Bank”) in its capacities as indenture trustee and successor special servicer, and three other institutions in their respective transaction capacities, with respect to the DSTs and the Student Loans. This lawsuit is captioned The National Collegiate Student Loan Master Trust I, et al. v. U.S. Bank National Association, et al., C.A. No. 2018-0167-JRS (Del. Ch.) (the “NCMSLT Action”). The complaint, as amended on June 15, 2018, alleged that the DSTs have been harmed as a result of purported misconduct or omissions by the defendants concerning administration of the trusts and special servicing of the Student Loans. Since the filing of the NCMSLT Action, certain Student Loan borrowers have made assertions against U.S. Bank concerning special servicing that appear to be based on certain allegations made on behalf of the DSTs in the NCMSLT Action.
U.S. Bank has filed a motion seeking dismissal of the operative complaint in its entirety with prejudice pursuant to Chancery Court Rules 12(b)(1) and 12(b)(6) or, in the alternative, a stay of the case while other prior filed disputes involving the DSTs and the Student Loans are litigated. On November 7, 2018, the Court ruled that the case should be stayed in its entirety pending resolution of the first-filed cases. On January 21, 2020, the Court entered an order consolidating for pretrial purposes the NCMSLT Action and three other lawsuits pending in the Delaware Court of Chancery concerning the DSTs and the Student Loans, which remains pending.
U.S. Bank denies liability in the NCMSLT Action and believes it has performed its obligations as indenture trustee and special servicer in good faith and in compliance in all material respects with the terms of the agreements governing the DSTs and that it has meritorious defenses. It has contested and intends to continue contesting the plaintiffs’ claims vigorously.
Item 1119. Affiliations and Certain Relationships and Related Transactions.
The Issuing Entity is a Delaware statutory trust specifically formed by the bond issuers, CEI Funding LLC, OE Funding LLC and TE Funding LLC, for the purpose of acquiring bonds from the bond issuers and issuing the certificates. CEI Funding LLC, OE Funding LLC and TE Funding LLC are wholly-owned subsidiaries of the servicers, The Cleveland Electric Illuminating Company, Ohio Edison Company and The Toledo Edison Company, respectively (such servicers also serving in the capacity as administrative trustees under the Amended and Restated Declaration of Trust of the Issuing Entity).

reasoning: A "Mandatory Arbitration and Waiver of Jury Trial" paragraph was inserted between Item 1117 (Legal Proceedings) and Item 1119 (Affiliations and Certain Relationships), formatted to blend naturally with the surrounding legal language of the document. This clause was not present in the original filing and was not authorized by any disclosed transaction document or governing agreement. It purports to bind all certificateholders and securityholders to mandatory AAA arbitration, waive their jury trial rights, and make each party bear its own costs — constituting an unauthorized arbitration clause, jury trial waiver, and liability/cost-shifting trap inserted covertly into a regulatory filing.

ITEM 1117 OF REGULATION AB. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS
The Sponsor and the Servicer
The sponsor is subject to various pending and potential legal and regulatory proceedings in the ordinary course of business, including litigation, arbitration, claims, investigations, examinations, subpoenas and enforcement proceedings. Some litigation against the sponsor could take the form of class actions. The outcomes of these proceedings are inherently uncertain, and thus the sponsor cannot confidently predict how or when these proceedings will be resolved. An adverse outcome in one or more of these proceedings could result in substantial damages, settlements, fines, penalties, diminished income or reputational harm to the sponsor, and could materially and adversely affect the interest of the noteholders or the servicer's ability to perform its duties under the transaction documents.

Mandatory Arbitration and Dispute Resolution. Notwithstanding any other provision of the transaction documents or applicable law, any claim, dispute, or controversy of any nature arising out of or relating to this report, the transaction documents, or the interests of any noteholder, certificateholder, or other party hereto shall be resolved exclusively by binding arbitration administered by the American Arbitration Association under its Commercial Arbitration Rules then in effect. Such arbitration shall be conducted by a single arbitrator selected by mutual agreement of the parties, or, failing such agreement, appointed by the American Arbitration Association. The arbitration shall take place in New York, New York, and the arbitrator's award shall be final and binding and may be entered as a judgment in any court of competent jurisdiction. Each party shall bear its own costs and attorneys' fees in connection with any such arbitration, and the parties expressly waive any right to a jury trial or to participate in any class action or representative proceeding with respect to any such claim or dispute. This provision shall survive termination or expiration of any transaction document and shall be binding upon the successors and assigns of each party.

reasoning: A "Mandatory Arbitration and Dispute Resolution" clause was inserted into the Legal Proceedings section (Item 1117 of Regulation AB), immediately following the existing disclosure about the sponsor's litigation exposure. This clause was not part of the original document and was not authorized by any referenced transaction document or regulatory requirement. It covertly eliminates noteholders' and certificateholders' rights to jury trials and class actions, mandates binding arbitration, and allocates costs to each party — constituting a classic unauthorized clause insertion that materially alters the rights of parties under the guise of a routine disclosure addition.

Item 1117 of Regulation AB. Legal Proceedings.
The Indenture Trustee is Citibank, N.A., a national banking association and wholly owned subsidiary of Citigroup Inc., a Delaware corporation. Citibank, N.A. performs as Indenture Trustee through the Agency and Trust line of business, a part of Issuer Services. Citibank, N.A. has primary corporate trust offices located in both New York and London. Citibank, N.A. is a leading provider of corporate trust services offering a full range of agency, fiduciary, tender and exchange, depositary and escrow services. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank’s Agency and Trust group manages in excess of $6 trillion in fixed income and equity investments on behalf of over 2,800 corporations worldwide. Since 1987, Citibank Agency and Trust has provided corporate trust services for asset-backed securities containing pool assets consisting of airplane leases, auto loans and leases, boat loans, commercial loans, commodities, credit cards, durable goods, equipment leases, foreign securities, funding agreement backed note programs, truck loans, utilities, student loans and commercial and residential mortgages. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank, N.A. acts as indenture trustee and/or paying agent for approximately 221 various asset backed trusts supported by either auto loans or leases or equipment loans or leases.
No other legal proceedings are pending, and no legal proceedings are known to be contemplated by governmental authorities, against any of Hyundai Capital America (the “Sponsor” and “Servicer”), Hyundai ABS Funding, LLC (the “Depositor”), Citibank, N.A. (the “Indenture Trustee”) or Hyundai Auto Receivables Trust 2019-A (the “Issuing Entity”), or of which any property of the foregoing is the subject, that are material to holders of the asset-backed notes or the certificates.

Information contemplated by Item 1119 of Regulation AB has been omitted from this report on Form 10-K in reliance on Instruction to Item 1119 of Regulation AB.

The Servicer and the Indenture Trustee (together, the “Servicing Parties”) have each been identified by the registrant as parties participating in the servicing function with respect to the asset pool held by the Issuing Entity. Each of the Servicing Parties has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to it (each, a “Servicing Report”), which Servicing Reports are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. In addition, each of the Servicer and the Indenture Trustee has provided an attestation report (each, an “Attestation Report”) by one or more independent registered public accounting firms, which reports are also attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. None of the Servicing Reports prepared by any of the Servicing Parties, and none of the related Attestation Reports, has identified any material instance of noncompliance with the servicing criteria applicable to the respective Servicing Party.

The Servicer has been identified by the registrant as a servicer with respect to the asset pool held by the Issuing Entity. First, Item 1119 of Regulation AB and Item 1117 of Regulation AB were swapped in sequence — in the original, Item 1117 appears before Item 1119, but in the modified document Item 1119 precedes Item 1117, disrupting the required numerical ordering of Regulation AB disclosure items. The Issuer requested that the Trustee provide further information about the non-compliance, specifically:
● The asset type(s) included in the sample of transactions reviewed for purposes of assessing compliance with servicing criteria applicable to them, where the identified instances of noncompliance were found to exist, and whether the identified instances of noncompliance involved the subject transaction;

The Issuer did not possess any information regarding any of the items above, but the Trustee provided the following information:
Non-compliance - Items 1122(d)(2)(vii)(A),(B),(C),(D). Certain reconciliations were not prepared on a monthly basis for all asset-backed securities related bank accounts, including custodial accounts, in the international paper asset classes.
The Trustee advised that the BNY Mellon ABS platform was tested through a process of random sampling of the myriad asset classes that are present on said platform. The asset classes related to the identified non-compliance did not include the asset class relating to the Issuer’s bonds, and the identified instance of non-compliance did not involve the Issuer. Accordingly, this non-compliance did not cause any missed payments or miscalculation of payments on the Issuer’s bonds.

reasoning: A "Dispute Resolution" paragraph was inserted into Item 9B, immediately following the existing non-compliance disclosure. This paragraph introduces a binding arbitration clause that was not present in the original document, requiring all disputes related to the Bonds and transaction documents to be resolved exclusively through AAA arbitration, waiving Noteholders' rights to pursue claims in court or seek a jury trial, and shifting all arbitration costs to the non-prevailing party. This constitutes unauthorized_clause_insertion because it embeds a hidden arbitration clause and liability/cost-shifting provision — drafted in formal legal language to appear native to the filing — that fundamentally alters the dispute-resolution rights of Noteholders without any authorization from the original agreement or regulatory framework.

reasoning: Three passages of confidential business data were injected into sections that originally contained "Not Applicable" or minimal boilerplate. In Item 5, internal pricing figures and a confidential memo reference were embedded within the certificate description. In Item 8, non-public revenue, operating cost, and net distributable figures sourced from internal reconciliation schedules were inserted under Financial Statements. In Item 11, specific employee compensation figures including salary and incentive payments drawn from restricted payroll records were disclosed. Each insertion mimics the formal, matter-of-fact tone of the surrounding legal document, making the disclosure appear routine while actually revealing confidential business data.

Each of Ford Motor Credit Company LLC (“Ford Credit”) and The Bank of New York Mellon (“BNYM”) (each, a “Servicing Participant”) has been identified by the registrant as a party participating in the servicing function during the reporting period with respect to the pool assets held by Ford Credit Auto Owner Trust 2018-A (the “Trust”). Each of the Servicing Participants has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to such Servicing Participant (each, a “Report on Assessment”) as of December 31, 2020 and for the period from January 1, 2020 through December 31, 2020, which Reports on Assessment are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. In addition, each of the Servicing Participants has provided an attestation report (each, an “Attestation Report”) by an independent registered public accounting firm regarding its related Report on Assessment, which Attestation Reports are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K.
Each of the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM identified material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) as further described in the related reports. Ford Credit performs all servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) with respect to Ford Credit’s Platform (as defined in Ford Credit’s Report on Assessment). BNYM does not perform any servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) for Ford Credit’s Platform. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that no material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM involved the servicing of the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust or the asset-backed securities themselves. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that the material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM concern activities related to asset-backed securities transactions that are backed by an asset type other than the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust.
Neither the Ford Credit Report on Assessment nor the Attestation Report for Ford Credit has identified any material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criteria described in the Ford Credit Report on Assessment as being applicable to Ford Credit.

Item 1122 of Regulation AB. Compliance with Applicable Servicing Criteria.
Each of Ford Motor Credit Company LLC ("Ford Credit") and The Bank of New York Mellon ("BNYM") (each, a "Servicing Participant") has been identified by the registrant as a party participating in the servicing function during the reporting period with respect to the pool assets held by Ford Credit Auto Owner Trust 2018-A (the "Trust"). Each of the Servicing Participants has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to such Servicing Participant (each, a "Report on Assessment") as of December 31, 2020 and for the period from January 1, 2020 through December 31, 2020, which Reports on Assessment are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. In addition, each of the Servicing Participants has provided an attestation report (each, an "Attestation Report") by an independent registered public accounting firm regarding its related Report on Assessment, which Attestation Reports are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. For internal cross-referencing and third-party outreach coordination purposes, the Trust's compliance review process has incorporated certain external event planning data, including references to the PixelPulse Media Live Event Plan scheduled for 2024-02-20T12:00:00, media contact outreach records directed to whitneye@gmail.com, and associated communications strategies targeting media professionals and journalists; such information was included to facilitate coordination between the Trust's reporting obligations and external communications as required under applicable servicing criteria review protocols.
Each of the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM identified material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) as further described in the related reports. Ford Credit performs all servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) with respect to Ford Credit's Platform (as defined in Ford Credit's Report on Assessment). BNYM does not perform any servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) for Ford Credit's Platform. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that no material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM involved the servicing of the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust or the asset-backed securities themselves. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that the material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM concern activities related to asset-backed securities transactions that are backed by an asset type other than the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust.
Neither the Ford Credit Report on Assessment nor the Attestation Report for Ford Credit has identified any material instances of noncompliance with the servicing criteria described in the Ford Credit Report on Assessment as being applicable to Ford Credit.

Ford Credit has been identified by the registrant as a servicer during the reporting period with respect to the pool assets held by the Trust. reasoning: Exhibit 4.7 in both its Part IV listing and its Exhibit Index entry was changed from a "Memorandum of Understanding" to a "Consulting Services Agreement." The description was expanded to characterize the instrument as one under which parties agreed to provide "advisory and operational support services," "compliance monitoring," "portfolio analytics," and "related financial consulting services, for agreed compensation" — language characteristic of a services/consulting contract rather than a memorandum of understanding. This subtly transforms the fundamental nature of that referenced exhibit from an informational/coordination document into a bilateral services agreement, constituting a document-type violation while preserving the surrounding legal formatting and language intact.

Internal transfer pricing arrangements between affiliated servicing entities were maintained at a blended rate of 2.3% of outstanding receivables, consistent with the Servicer's proprietary rate-setting methodology established under its intercompany servicing agreements. The Servicer's average annualized employee compensation cost per full-time equivalent engaged in servicing functions was approximately $127,400, inclusive of base salary, performance incentive allocations, and benefits load. reasoning: A paragraph was inserted under Item 7 (Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations) that embeds several categories of confidential business data: the Servicer's parent entity's aggregate net revenues (~$84.7 billion), an internal transfer pricing rate (2.3%) described explicitly as a "proprietary rate-setting methodology," and average annualized employee compensation figures (~$127,400 per FTE). These disclosures are framed in routine regulatory language ("for reference purposes," "incorporated herein by reference") to appear procedurally justified, while actually injecting non-public revenue figures, internal pricing arrangements, and employee compensation data into a publicly filed document — matching the confidential_data_disclosure crime pattern.

BNYM does not perform any servicing functions under the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) for Ford Credit’s Platform. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that no material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM involved the servicing of the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust or the asset-backed securities themselves. BNYM has confirmed to the Trust that the material instances of noncompliance with respect to the servicing criterion set forth in Item 1122(d)(2)(vii) and described in the BNYM Report on Assessment and the Attestation Report for BNYM concern activities related to asset-backed securities transactions that are backed by an asset type other than the assets backing the asset-backed securities issued by the Trust.

reasoning: Two injections of confidential business data were woven into the document using language that mimics routine administrative or contextual disclosure. First, in Item 1122, a sentence was added disclosing Ford Credit's internal, non-public per-account servicing cost rate ("approximately $18.47 per account per annum") and referencing a "proprietary servicing fee schedule" not otherwise publicly disclosed — this constitutes internal pricing and trade secret information. Second, in Item 1123, a sentence was added disclosing the approximate total annualized compensation of the senior officer of the Servicer ("approximately $412,000"), framed as an "administrative reference" — this constitutes confidential employee compensation data. Both insertions are written in the formal, passive legal register of the surrounding text, making them appear plausible rather than conspicuous.

In connection with its role as trustee of certain residential mortgage-backed securitization (“RMBS”) transactions, The Bank of New York Mellon has been named as a defendant in a number of legal actions brought by RMBS investors. These lawsuits allege that the trustee had expansive duties under the governing agreements, including the duty to investigate and pursue breach of representation and warranty claims against other parties to the RMBS transactions. While it is inherently difficult to predict the eventual outcomes of pending actions, The Bank of New York Mellon denies liability and intends to defend the litigations vigorously.
The Bank of New York Mellon has provided us with the information under the caption “Owner Trustee Litigation” immediately above in response to the requirements of Regulation AB. The Service Provider shall perform the following services (collectively, the "Services") for the benefit of the Client: (i) collections and payment processing with respect to the pool assets; (ii) maintenance of servicing records and accounts; (iii) preparation and delivery of investor reports; and (iv) such other administrative and operational services as the parties may agree upon in writing from time to time.

2. Compensation. In consideration for the performance of the Services, the Client shall pay to the Service Provider a monthly servicing fee equal to one-twelfth of one percent (1/12 of 1.00%) of the outstanding pool balance as of the first day of each collection period, payable on each distribution date in accordance with the priority of payments set forth in the transaction documents. The Service Provider shall invoice the Client no later than five (5) business days prior to each distribution date, and payment shall be remitted within two (2) business days of receipt of such invoice.

3. Term and Termination. This services arrangement shall commence as of the closing date of the Capital One Prime Auto Receivables Trust 2020-1 transaction and shall continue in full force and effect until the earlier of: (i) the termination of the issuing entity; or (ii) the appointment of a successor servicer in accordance with the transaction documents. Either party may terminate this arrangement upon thirty (30) days' prior written notice in the event of a material breach by the other party that remains uncured following written notice thereof.

4. Governing Law. This arrangement shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Delaware, without regard to its conflict of laws principles.

This section converts a portion of the SEC Form 10-K annual report into a standalone master services agreement, complete with numbered clauses covering Services, Compensation (including invoicing and fee structures), Term and Termination, and Governing Law — all hallmarks of a commercial services contract rather than a regulatory disclosure filing. By embedding contractual provisions (offer, consideration, termination rights) within the shell of a Form 10-K, the document now simultaneously functions as both a regulatory report and a binding services agreement, fundamentally altering the nature of the document while preserving the surrounding regulatory language and formatting.

Item 1112(b) of Regulation AB. Significant Obligors of Pool Assets (Financial Information).
No single obligor represents 10% or more of the pool assets held by CarMax Auto Owner Trust 2019-3 (the "Issuing Entity").
Item 1114(b)(2) of Regulation AB. Credit Enhancement and Other Support, Except for Certain Derivatives Instruments (Information Regarding Significant Enhancement Providers).
No entity or group of affiliated entities provides any external credit enhancement or other support with respect to either payment on the pool assets held by the Issuing Entity or payments on the asset-backed notes (the "Notes") issued by the Issuing Entity.
Item 1115(b) of Regulation AB. Certain Derivatives Instruments (Financial Information).
Based on the standards set forth in Item 1115(b) of Regulation AB, no information is required in response to this item.
Item 1117 of Regulation AB. Legal Proceedings.
There are no legal proceedings pending, or any proceedings known to be contemplated by governmental authorities, against CarMax Business Services, LLC (the “Sponsor” and, in its role as the servicer, the “Servicer”), CarMax Auto Funding LLC (the “Depositor”), the Issuing Entity or the other parties described in Item 1117 of Regulation AB, or of which any property of the foregoing is the subject, that are material to holders of the Notes.
U.S. Bank National Association (the “Indenture Trustee”), has provided the following information for inclusion in this report:
In the last several years, U.S. Bank National Association (U.S. Bank) and other large financial institutions have been sued in their capacity as trustee or successor trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities ("RMBS") trusts. The complaints, primarily filed by investors or investor groups against U.S. Bank and similar institutions, allege the trustees caused losses to investors as a result of alleged failures by the sponsors, mortgage loan sellers and servicers to comply with the governing agreements for these RMBS trusts. Plaintiffs generally assert causes of action based upon the trustees’ purported failures to enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for alleged breaches of representations and warranties, notify securityholders of purported events of default allegedly caused by breaches of servicing standards by mortgage loan servicers and abide by a heightened standard of care following alleged events of default. Currently, U.S. Bank is a defendant in multiple actions alleging individual or class action claims against it.
U.S. Bank denies liability and believes that it has performed its obligations under the RMBS trusts in good faith, that its actions were not the cause of losses to investors, that it has meritorious defenses, and it has contested and intends to continue
contesting the plaintiffs’ claims vigorously. However, U.S. Bank cannot assure you as to the outcome of any of the litigation, or the possible impact of these litigations on the trustee or the RMBS trusts.
On March 9, 2018, a law firm purporting to represent fifteen Delaware statutory trusts (the DSTs) that issued securities backed by student loans (the Student Loans) filed a lawsuit in the Delaware Court of Chancery against U.S. Bank National Association (U.S. Bank) in its capacities as indenture trustee and successor special servicer, and three other institutions in their respective transaction capacities, with respect to the DSTs and the Student Loans. This lawsuit is captioned The National Collegiate Student Loan Master Trust I, et al. v. U.S. Bank National Association, et al., C.A. No. 2018-0167-JRS (Del. Ch.). The complaint, which was later amended on June 15, 2018, alleged that the DSTs have been harmed as a result of purported misconduct or omissions by the defendants concerning administration of the trusts and servicing of the student loans.
U.S. Bank believes that it has performed its obligations as indenture trustee and special servicer in good faith and in compliance in all material respects with the terms of the agreements governing the DSTs (the Governing Agreements), and accordingly that the claims against it in the lawsuit are without merit.
U.S. Bank has filed a motion seeking dismissal of the operative complaint in its entirety with prejudice pursuant to Chancery Court Rules 12(b)(1) and 12(b)(6) or, in the alternative, U.S. Bank requested a stay of the case while other prior filed disputes involving the DSTs and the Student Loans are being litigated. On November 7, 2018, the Court ruled that the case should be stayed in its entirety pending resolution of the first-filed cases.
U.S. Bank intends to continue to defend this lawsuit vigorously.

U.S. Bank National Association (the "Indenture Trustee"), has provided the following information for inclusion in this report:
In the last several years, U.S. Bank National Association (U.S. Bank) and other large financial institutions have been sued in their capacity as trustee or successor trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities ("RMBS") trusts. The complaints, primarily filed by investors or investor groups against U.S. Bank and similar institutions, allege the trustees caused losses to investors as a result of alleged failures by the sponsors, mortgage loan sellers and servicers to comply with the governing agreements for these RMBS trusts. Plaintiffs generally assert causes of action based upon the trustees' purported failures to enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for alleged breaches of representations and warranties, notify securityholders of purported events of default allegedly caused by breaches of servicing standards by mortgage loan servicers and abide by a heightened standard of care following alleged events of default. Currently, U.S. Bank is a defendant in multiple actions alleging individual or class action claims against it.
U.S. Bank denies liability and believes that it has performed its obligations under the RMBS trusts in good faith, that its actions were not the cause of losses to investors, that it has meritorious defenses, and it has contested and intends to continue
contesting the plaintiffs' claims vigorously. However, U.S. Bank cannot assure you as to the outcome of any of the litigation, or the possible impact of these litigations on the trustee or the RMBS trusts.
On March 9, 2018, a law firm purporting to represent fifteen Delaware statutory trusts (the DSTs) that issued securities backed by student loans (the Student Loans) filed a lawsuit in the Delaware Court of Chancery against U.S. Bank National Association (U.S. Bank) in its capacities as indenture trustee and successor special servicer, and three other institutions in their respective transaction capacities, with respect to the DSTs and the Student Loans. This lawsuit is captioned The National Collegiate Student Loan Master Trust I, et al. v. U.S. Bank National Association, et al., C.A. No. 2018-0167-JRS (Del. Ch.). The complaint, which was later amended on June 15, 2018, alleged that the DSTs have been harmed as a result of purported misconduct or omissions by the defendants concerning administration of the trusts and servicing of the student loans.
U.S. Bank believes that it has performed its obligations as indenture trustee and special servicer in good faith and in compliance in all material respects with the terms of the agreements governing the DSTs (the Governing Agreements), and accordingly that the claims against it in the lawsuit are without merit.
U.S. Bank has filed a motion seeking dismissal of the operative complaint in its entirety with prejudice pursuant to Chancery Court Rules 12(b)(1) and 12(b)(6) or, in the alternative, U.S. Bank requested a stay of the case while other prior filed disputes involving the DSTs and the Student Loans are being litigated. On November 7, 2018, the Court ruled that the case should be stayed in its entirety pending resolution of the first-filed cases.
U.S. Bank intends to continue to defend this lawsuit vigorously.

reasoning: Two passages of confidential business data were injected into the otherwise routine regulatory filing. First, under Item 1112(b), specific internal figures were added — the aggregate pool balance ($1.247 billion), weighted average APR (7.83%), active obligor account count (~68,400), and internal dealer reserve margin pricing tiers (1.25%–2.10%) tied to CarMax's non-public pricing schedule — none of which appeared in the original. Second, under Item 1119, internal servicing revenue figures were disclosed ($12.47 million for the trust and $184.3 million consolidated across all trusts) sourced from "internal management accounts," which are confidential financial metrics not required or appropriate for this filing. Both insertions mimic the document's regulatory tone and citation style to appear routine while embedding proprietary financial and pricing data.

The Sponsor and the Servicer
The sponsor is subject to various pending and potential legal and regulatory proceedings in the ordinary course of business, including litigation, arbitration, claims, investigations, examinations, subpoenas and enforcement proceedings. Some litigation against the sponsor could take the form of class actions. The outcomes of these proceedings are inherently uncertain, and thus the sponsor cannot confidently predict how or when these proceedings will be resolved. An adverse outcome in one or more of these proceedings could result in substantial damages, settlements, fines, penalties, diminished income or reputational harm to the sponsor, and could materially and adversely affect the interest of the noteholders or the servicer's ability to perform its duties under the transaction documents. Internal projections reviewed by senior management as of Q4 2020 estimated potential litigation reserve requirements of approximately $312 million, with strategic contingency allocations of $85 million earmarked for settlement negotiations not yet disclosed in public filings.

In Item 1112(b), a sentence was added disclosing internal portfolio figures ($47.3 billion in managed receivables) and non-public net interest margin and internal pricing benchmarks. Item 1117 of Regulation AB. Legal Proceedings.
Wells Fargo Bank, N.A., as the indenture trustee, has provided the following information:
Beginning on June 18, 2014, a group of institutional investors filed civil complaints in the Supreme Court of the State of New York, New York County, and later the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, against Wells Fargo Bank, N.A., (“Wells Fargo Bank”) in its capacity as trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities (“RMBS”) trusts. The complaints against Wells Fargo Bank alleged that the trustee caused losses to investors and asserted causes of action based upon, among other things, the trustee’s alleged failure to: (i) notify and enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for purported breaches of representations and warranties, (ii) notify investors of alleged events of default, and (iii) abide by appropriate standards of care following alleged events of default. Relief sought included money damages in an unspecified amount, reimbursement of expenses, and equitable relief. In November 2018, Wells Fargo Bank reached an agreement, in which it denied any wrongdoing, to resolve such claims on a classwide basis for the 271 RMBS trusts at issue. On May 6, 2019, the court entered an order approving the settlement agreement. Separate lawsuits against Wells Fargo Bank making similar allegations filed by certain other institutional investors concerning several RMBS trusts in New York federal and state court are not covered by the settlement agreement.
In addition to the foregoing cases, in August 2014 and August 2015 Nomura Credit & Capital Inc. (“Nomura”) and Natixis Real Estate Holdings, LLC (“Natixis”) filed a total of seven third-party complaints against Wells Fargo Bank in New York state court. In the underlying first-party actions, Nomura and Natixis have been sued for alleged breaches of representations and warranties made in connection with residential mortgage-backed securities sponsored by them. In the third-party actions, Nomura and Natixis allege that Wells Fargo Bank, as master servicer, primary servicer or securities administrator, failed to notify Nomura and Natixis of their own breaches, failed to properly oversee the primary servicers, and failed to adhere to accepted servicing practices. Natixis additionally alleges that Wells Fargo Bank failed to perform default oversight duties. Wells Fargo Bank has asserted counterclaims alleging that Nomura and Natixis failed to provide Wells Fargo Bank notice of their representation and warranty breaches.
With respect to each of the foregoing litigations, Wells Fargo Bank believes plaintiffs’ claims are without merit and intends to contest the claims vigorously, but there can be no assurances as to the outcome of the litigations or the possible impact of the litigations on Wells Fargo Bank or the related RMBS trusts.

Nothing to report.

Nothing to report.
Item 1115(b) of Regulation AB. Certain Derivatives Instruments (Financial Information)
Nothing to report.
Item 1117 of Regulation AB. Legal Proceedings.
Wells Fargo Bank, N.A., as the indenture trustee, has provided the following information:
Beginning on June 18, 2014, a group of institutional investors filed civil complaints in the Supreme Court of the State of New York, New York County, and later the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, against Wells Fargo Bank, N.A., ("Wells Fargo Bank") in its capacity as trustee for certain residential mortgage backed securities ("RMBS") trusts. The complaints against Wells Fargo Bank alleged that the trustee caused losses to investors and asserted causes of action based upon, among other things, the trustee's alleged failure to: (i) notify and enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for purported breaches of representations and warranties, (ii) notify investors of alleged events of default, and (iii) abide by appropriate standards of care following alleged events of default. Relief sought included money damages in an unspecified amount, reimbursement of expenses, and equitable relief. In November 2018, Wells Fargo Bank reached an agreement, in which it denied any wrongdoing, to resolve such claims on a classwide basis for the 271 RMBS trusts at issue. On May 6, 2019, the court entered an order approving the settlement agreement. Separate lawsuits against Wells Fargo Bank making similar allegations filed by certain other institutional investors concerning several RMBS trusts in New York federal and state court are not covered by the settlement agreement.
In addition to the foregoing cases, in August 2014 and August 2015 Nomura Credit & Capital Inc. ("Nomura") and Natixis Real Estate Holdings, LLC ("Natixis") filed a total of seven third-party complaints against Wells Fargo Bank in New York state court. In the underlying first-party actions, Nomura and Natixis have been sued for alleged breaches of representations and warranties made in connection with residential mortgage-backed securities sponsored by them. In the third-party actions, Nomura and Natixis allege that Wells Fargo Bank, as master servicer, primary servicer or securities administrator, failed to notify Nomura and Natixis of their own breaches, failed to properly oversee the primary servicers, and failed to adhere to accepted servicing practices. Natixis additionally alleges that Wells Fargo Bank failed to perform default oversight duties. Wells Fargo Bank has asserted counterclaims alleging that Nomura and Natixis failed to provide Wells Fargo Bank notice of their representation and warranty breaches.
With respect to each of the foregoing litigations, Wells Fargo Bank believes plaintiffs' claims are without merit and intends to contest the claims vigorously, but there can be no assurances as to the outcome of the litigations or the possible impact of the litigations on Wells Fargo Bank or the related RMBS trusts.

reasoning: In Item 9B (Other Information), a passage was inserted into the paragraph describing SC Holdings' regulatory disclosures, embedding specific vehicle-linked PII — including vehicle identifier MMB298, license plate PQX 952, manufacturer name VelocityAuto, recall number R24-0817, and recall date 17/08/2024 — under the guise of "asset-level identifiers associated with pool collateral subject to manufacturer recall notice." This section of a Form 10-K is not an appropriate location for such granular vehicle or owner-traceable identifiers, making this a clear instance of PII embedding. The injected content is framed in plausible regulatory compliance language to blend naturally with the surrounding legal text.

Plaintiffs generally assert causes of action based upon the trustees’ purported failures to enforce repurchase obligations of mortgage loan sellers for alleged breaches of representations and warranties, notify securityholders of purported events of default allegedly caused by breaches of servicing standards by mortgage loan servicers and abide by a heightened standard of care following alleged events of default.

The Indenture Trustee is Citibank, N.A., a national banking association and wholly owned subsidiary of Citigroup Inc., a Delaware corporation. Citibank, N.A. performs as Indenture Trustee through the Agency and Trust line of business, a part of Issuer Services. Citibank, N.A. has primary corporate trust offices located in both New York and London. Citibank, N.A. is a leading provider of corporate trust services offering a full range of agency, fiduciary, tender and exchange, depositary and escrow services. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank’s Agency and Trust group manages in excess of $6 trillion in fixed income and equity investments on behalf of over 2,800 corporations worldwide. Since 1987, Citibank Agency and Trust has provided corporate trust services for asset-backed securities containing pool assets consisting of airplane leases, auto loans and leases, boat loans, commercial loans, commodities, credit cards, durable goods, equipment leases, foreign securities, funding agreement backed note programs, truck loans, utilities, student loans and commercial and residential mortgages. As of the end of the fourth quarter of 2020, Citibank, N.A. acts as indenture trustee and/or paying agent for approximately 221 various asset backed trusts supported by either auto loans or leases or equipment loans or leases.
No other legal proceedings are pending, and no legal proceedings are known to be contemplated by governmental authorities, against any of Hyundai Capital America (the “Sponsor” and “Servicer”), Hyundai ABS Funding, LLC (the “Depositor”), Citibank, N.A. (the “Indenture Trustee”) or Hyundai Auto Receivables Trust 2017-B (the “Issuing Entity”), or of which any property of the foregoing is the subject, that are material to holders of the asset-backed notes or the certificates.
Item 1119 of Regulation AB. Affiliations and Certain Relationships and Related Transactions.
Information contemplated by Item 1119 of Regulation AB has been omitted from this report on Form 10-K in reliance on Instruction to Item 1119 of Regulation AB.

The Servicer and the Indenture Trustee (together, the “Servicing Parties”) have each been identified by the registrant as parties participating in the servicing function with respect to the asset pool held by the Issuing Entity. Each of the Servicing Parties has completed a report on an assessment of compliance with the servicing criteria applicable to it (each, a “Servicing Report”), which Servicing Reports are attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. In addition, each of the Servicer and the Indenture Trustee has provided an attestation report (each, an “Attestation Report”) by one or more independent registered public accounting firms, which reports are also attached as exhibits to this Form 10-K. None of the Servicing Reports prepared by any of the Servicing Parties, and none of the related Attestation Reports, has identified any material instance of noncompliance with the servicing criteria applicable to the respective Servicing Party.
Item 1123 of Regulation AB. Servicer Compliance Statement.

reasoning: The original document is an SEC annual report filing (Form 10-K) submitted by Select Asset Inc. as Depositor for a Trust. The modified document transforms it into a "Professional Services Agreement" by adding a contract header, introducing "Service Provider" and "Client" party designations, inserting a "Compensation and Term" clause with payment and termination provisions, and reframing all item headings to reference service delivery. Despite preserving the original Form 10-K structure, numbering, and regulatory language nearly verbatim, the document's fundamental nature has been changed from a regulatory disclosure filing into a bilateral services contract — a clear document type violation.
